urinal cake 2024-09-17 09:02 p.m.
While, yes, the petitioner has maybe been more careful about traffic laws, their argument that they have ascertained a "better sense of discipline in the community" and has strived to improve relations with law enforcement agencies, this is generally untrue. The Mayflower Bureau of Investigation recently launched an investigation (and is pursuing charges) for Felony & Gross Misconduct into the petitioner and was courteous enough to reach out to the petitioner, informing them of some surface-level information and wondering if the petitioner wanted to submit for some questioning. Instead of taking that opportunity gracefully, the petitioner practically spat in the face of the MBI employee, vehemently refusing to submit to any type of questioning, and even referring to the agent as "little man." While the petitioner contends they have tried to improve relations with law enforcement, this type of hostile behavior toward a law enforcement agency while they tried to extend an olive branch is not the behavior of a person who has "better[ed]" themself.

Additionally, driving through a red light and in the opposite lanes of travel near the Mersea CD, an area of high vehicular congestion and foot traffic, is outright dangerous. To have committed such an act in Medford or Woodbury, the Department of Justice may have been more lenient about the offense. In an area like that, however, simply excusing that behavior is not in the interest of the Justice Department.
